13-year-old Emtinan is working towards becoming a pediatrician or a gynecologist. But violence has cost her a precious year of school in Yemen. 

The chaos of conflict and COVID-19 has wreaked havoc on children's access to education. Over 2 million children have been displaced by war, and just as many are out of school.

UNICEF is helping provide safe places to learn, materials and teacher training — but more than anything, the children of Yemen need peace.

node.title: The cost of war in Yemen

node.text:
This is the impact of malnutrition on children in South Sudan.

UNICEF is on the ground supporting children on the brink with health and nutrition services - but we need your help. Save a life by donating today. https://uni.cf/on-the-brink

node.text:
For many mothers, the return to work is a barrier to breastfeeding their babies. 

That’s why UNICEF is calling on governments and businesses to support  family-friendly policies which give mothers the time and space to breastfeed. This includes at least 18-weeks paid maternity leave, safe places for breastfeeding in the workplace; access to affordable and good-quality childcare; and universal child benefits and adequate wages.

#WorldBreastfeedingWeek

© UNICEF/UNI166592/Liu

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by UNICEF on August 02, 2021. May be an image of text that says '156 million children still out of school due to COVID-19. unicef for every child'.

node.text:
These children can’t go another day out of the classroom. 

After 18 months of education disruption due to COVID-19, getting students back to school and providing them with the support they need to readjust and catch up on their learning is critical. Their futures depend on it.

node.text: Many of us have experienced loneliness, anxiety and fear during the  COVID-19 pandemic - these emotions can be especially difficult to process for children and young people. Take the time to check in and encourage your friends and family to regularly share how they are feeling. #MentalHealthAction

node.text:
Classrooms cannot continue to look like this.

Over 156 million students in 19 countries are still affected by full school closures due to COVID-19, facing an unprecedented second year of disruption to their education. To protect children's futures, we must get them back to school as soon as possible.

node.text:
Health centres have been attacked and starved of electricity and supplies during Ethiopia’s Tigray conflict, and it’s hitting children hardest.

At a time where COVID-19 is making health services more important than ever, conflict is severing family’s access to doctors, antibiotics, emergency nutrition and vaccines. 

To save lives and deliver life-saving supplies, UNICEF and partners need urgent, safe and sustained access. More than anything, the children of Tigray need peace.

© UNICEF/UN0494082/Nesbitt

We can build a healthier world - and it starts from birth. 

By supporting more mothers to breastfeed within the first hour of birth and exclusively for their baby’s first six months, we’re providing children with a powerful line of defence against infection and malnutrition.

#WorldBreastfeedingWeek

node.text:
Baby Wegahta was only six days old when her family fled their one-room home to escape fighting in Ethiopia’s Tigray region. 

Due to the disruption caused by conflict and COVID-19, she’s one of 100,000 children facing life-threatening malnutrition.

As UNICEF and partners reach families with lifesaving health care and nutrition supplies, we’re calling for safe and sustained access. @unicefethiopia 

© UNICEF/UN0494131/Nesbitt

We cannot risk more disruption to education.

To prevent the COVID-19 pandemic from having a life-long impact on an entire generation of children and young people, especially the most vulnerable, schools must reopen for in-person learning as soon as possible - and stay open.

© UNICEF/UN0414993/Galstyan

node.text:
On entering previously inaccessible parts of Ethiopia’s conflict-ravaged region of Tigray for the first time in months, our worst fears were realised. Without urgent action, over 100,000 children will face life-threatening malnutrition in the next year.

Through COVID-19, UNICEF and partners are providing desperate families with emergency health and nutrition services. 

As we scale up our support, all parties to the conflict MUST protect children from harm.

© UNICEF/UN0494085/Nesbitt
